We use Google API client to marshal/unmarshal JSON to Java types. If you have a Tenant class defined as follows:
class Tenant {
  @Key("tenantId")
  private String tenantId;

  @Key("displayName")
  private String displayName;
}

...then you can construct an instance of it from JSON as follows:
Tenant tenant = jsonFactory.createJsonParser(jsonString).parse(Tenant.class);

So AutoValue doesn't add anything to this flow as far as I can see. Create and Update classes are essentially builders, and I can see the value in using AutoValue for them.
